v%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Femmys-best-worst-moments-2024-9%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1726463778000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66e7b93dd17aa3c7b2b2beff%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Femmys-best-worst-moments-2024-9%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%2076th%20Primetime%20Emmy%20Awards%20had%20some%20great%20moments%2C%20like%20Candice%20Bergen's%20dig%20at%20JD%20Vance.%20It%20also%20had%20some%20cringeworthy%20ones.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22phaasch%40businessinsider.com%20(Palmer%20Haasch)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A121%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Femmys-best-worst-moments-2024-9%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Earth%20May%20Have%20Had%20A%20Ring%20Like%20Saturn%2C%20Hidden%20Craters%20Reveal%20Evidence%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20rings%20of%20Saturn%20are%20some%20of%20the%20most%20famous%20and%20spectacular%20objects%20in%20the%20Solar%20System.%20Earth%20may%20once%20have%20had%20something%20similar.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1016%2Fj.epsl.2024.118991%5C%22%3Ea%20paper%20published%20last%20week%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20Earth%20%26amp%3B%20Planetary%20Science%20Letters%2C%20my%20colleagues%20and%20I%20present%20evidence%20that%20Earth%20may%20have%20had%20a%20ring.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20existence%20of%20such%20a%20ring%2C%20forming%20around%20466%20million%20years%20ago%20and%20persisting%20for%20a%20few%20tens%20of%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20could%20explain%20several%20puzzles%20in%20our%20planet's%20past.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch3%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20case%20for%20a%20ringed%20Earth%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh3%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESo%20it's%20extremely%20unlikely%20that%20all%2021%20craters%20from%20this%20period%20would%20form%20close%20to%20the%20equator%20if%20they%20were%20unrelated%20to%20one%20another.%20We%20would%20expect%20to%20see%20many%20other%20craters%20at%20higher%20latitudes%20as%20well.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20think%20the%20best%20explanation%20for%20all%20this%20evidence%20is%20that%20a%20large%20asteroid%20broke%20up%20during%20a%20close%20encounter%20with%20Earth.%20Over%20several%20tens%20of%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20the%20asteroid's%20debris%20rained%20down%20onto%20Earth%2C%20creating%20the%20pattern%20of%20craters%2C%20sediments%20and%20tsunamis%20we%20describe%20above.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch3%3E%3Cstrong%3EHow%20rings%20form%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh3%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EYou%20may%20know%20that%20Saturn%20isn't%20the%20only%20planet%20with%20rings.%20Jupiter%2C%20Neptune%20and%20Uranus%20have%20less%20obvious%20rings%2C%20too.%20Some%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fngeo2742%5C%22%3Escientists%20have%20even%20suggested%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20Phobos%20and%20Deimos%2C%20the%20small%20moons%20of%20Mars%2C%20may%20be%20remnants%20of%20an%20ancient%20ring.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESo%20we%20know%20a%20lot%20about%20how%20rings%20form.%20Here's%20how%20it%20works.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cfigcaption%3E%3Cspan%3ESaturn%20backlit%20by%20the%20Sun%2C%20taken%20by%20the%20Cassini%20spacecraft.%3C%2Fspan%3E%20%3Cspan%3E%3Cspan%3ECassini%20Imaging%20Team%20%2F%20SSI%20%2F%20JPL%20%2F%20ESA%20%2F%20NASA%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhen%20a%20small%20body%20(like%20an%20asteroid)%20passes%20close%20to%20a%20large%20body%20(like%20a%20planet)%2C%20it%20gets%20stretched%20by%20gravity.%20If%20it%20gets%20close%20enough%20(inside%20a%20distance%20called%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FRoche_limit%5C%22%3ERoche%20limit%3C%2Fa%3E)%2C%20the%20small%20body%20will%20break%20apart%20into%20lots%20of%20tiny%20pieces%20and%20a%20small%20number%20of%20bigger%20pieces.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAll%20those%20fragments%20will%20be%20jostled%20around%20and%20gradually%20evolve%20into%20a%20debris%20ring%20orbiting%20the%20equator%20of%20the%20larger%20body.%20Over%20time%2C%20the%20material%20in%20the%20ring%20will%20fall%20down%20to%20the%20larger%20body%2C%20where%20the%20larger%20pieces%20will%20form%20impact%20craters.%20These%20craters%20will%20be%20located%20close%20to%20the%20equator.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESo%20if%20Earth%20destroyed%20and%20captured%20a%20passing%20asteroid%20around%20466%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20it%20would%20explain%20the%20anomalous%20locations%20of%20the%20impact%20craters%2C%20the%20meteorite%20debris%20in%20sedimentary%20rocks%2C%20craters%20and%20tsunamis%2C%20and%20the%20meteorites'%20relatively%20brief%20exposure%20to%20space%20radiation.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch3%3E%3Cstrong%3EA%20giant%20sunshade%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh3%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBack%20then%2C%20the%20continents%20were%20in%20different%20positions%20due%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DPA8r3FVw46c%5C%22%3Econtinental%20drift%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Much%20of%20North%20America%2C%20Europe%20and%20Australia%20were%20close%20to%20the%20equator%2C%20whereas%20Africa%20and%20South%20America%20were%20at%20higher%20southern%20latitudes.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20ring%20would%20have%20been%20around%20the%20equator.%20And%20since%20Earth's%20axis%20is%20tilted%20relative%20to%20its%20orbit%20around%20the%20Sun%2C%20the%20ring%20would%20have%20shaded%20parts%20of%20Earth's%20surface.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20shading%20in%20turn%20might%20have%20caused%20global%20cooling%2C%20as%20less%20sunlight%20reached%20the%20planet's%20surface.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20brings%20us%20to%20another%20interesting%20puzzle.%20Around%20465%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20our%20planet%20began%20cooling%20dramatically.%20By%20445%20million%20years%20ago%20it%20was%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FHirnantian%5C%22%3EHirnantian%20Ice%20Age%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20coldest%20period%20in%20the%20past%20half%20a%20billion%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWas%20a%20ring-shading%20Earth%20responsible%20for%20this%20extreme%20cooling%3F%20The%20next%20step%20in%20our%20scientific%20sleuthing%20is%20to%20make%20mathematical%20models%20of%20how%20asteroids%20break%20up%20and%20disperse%2C%20and%20how%20the%20resulting%20ring%20evolves%20over%20time.%20This%20will%20set%20the%20scene%20for%20climate%20modelling%20that%20explores%20how%20much%20cooling%20could%20be%20imposed%20by%20such%20a%20ring.%3Cimg%20referrerpolicy%3D%5C%22no-referrer-when-downgrade%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcounter.theconversation.com%2Fcontent%2F239068%2Fcount.gif%3Fdistributor%3Drepublish-lightbox-basic%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20Conversation%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fprofiles%2Fandrew-tomkins-264027%5C%22%3EAndrew%20Tomkins%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Geologist%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Finstitutions%2Fmonash-university-1065%5C%22%3EMonash%20University%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20article%20is%20republished%20from%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%5C%22%3EThe%20Conversation%3C%2Fa%3E%20under%20a%20Creative%20Commons%20license.%20Read%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fhidden-craters-reveal-earth-may-once-have-had-a-ring-like-saturn-239068%5C%22%3Eoriginal%20article%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3E(Except%20for%20the%20headline%2C%20this%20story%20has%20not%20been%20edited%20by%20NDTV%20staff%20and%20is%20published%20from%20a%20syndicated%20feed.)%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1726463400000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fc.ndtvimg.com%2F2024-09%2Fcfer46vg_earth-ring-generic_625x300_16_September_24.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ndtv.com%2Fworld-news%2Fearth-may-have-had-a-ring